                                <foliation xml:id="modern">The fragment is foliated with the numbers
                                    1-5, [i] in Arabic numerals, in pencil, recto, upper
                                    right.</foliation>

                                <foliation xml:id="earlier">The fragment also retains foliation from
                                    the source manuscript, not original to its production: the
                                    numbers 163-167 in Greek numerals, in black ink, recto, upper
                                    right.</foliation>

                                <collation>
                                    <list>
                                        <item>Quire 1<hi rend="superscript">8-3</hi>
                                            <locus from="1r" to="[i] verso"> ff. 1-5, [i] </locus>
                                            <note>This quire of five surviving folios followed by a
                                                stub was probably originally a quaternion, in which
                                                the cancelled stub was the seventh original folio,
                                                while the outermost bifolio, forming the original
                                                first and eighth folios, has been lost. In this case
                                                the eighth folio was probably cancelled prior to the
                                                whole bifolio being lost, as the text appears to
                                                have continued from this point without loss. It may
                                                also have been a ternion of which the last folio has
                                                been cancelled, without loss of text, although the
                                                construction of the quire with hair side outermost
                                                which this would require would be unusual. However,
                                                the foliation of the Sinai fragment ends with 161,
                                                and there is a gap between the end of the text in
                                                that fragment and the beginning of this one, of a
                                                length corresponding to the content of a single
                                                folio, indicating that one intervening folio has
                                                been lost. This would tend in favour of the
                                                hypothesis that one folio was lost from the
                                                beginning of this quire.</note>
                              </item>
                                    </list>
                                </collation>

                                <condition>There are numerous small tears to the edges of the
                                    folios, most severely in <locus from="2r" to="2v">f. 2</locus>,
                                    where one tear has been repaired with stitching. The leaves are
                                    cockled, and there are areas of dirt and drops of
                                    wax.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>

                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="2" rulingMedium="hardpoint" topLine="below" writtenLines="30">Two columns of 30 lines each.
